article.description: Michael Olowakandi and Elton Brand controlled the inside while Quentin Richardson and Darius Miles provided their usual spark off the bench to lead the Clippers to a 96-75 rout of the Wizards.

article.headline: Clippers close to within a game of No. 8 spot
article.linkText: Clippers win 4th in row; one game out of playoffs
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Elton Brand got accustomed to winning at Duke, which made his two years with the Chicago Bulls all the more difficult.
Brand

Now, he's part of a winner again. And with the Los Angeles Clippers, of all teams. Brand recorded his 10th straight double-double, and Michael Olowokandi had 22 points and 11 rebounds Wednesday night as the surging Clippers beat the Washington Wizards 96-75. Brand had 19 points, 15 rebounds, five assists and four blocked shots as the Clippers extended their winning streak to four games -- their longest since they won four in a row nearly 13 months ago. "This feels great for me," said Brand, the first overall selection in the 1999 NBA draft who was traded by the Bulls to the Clippers last summer. "I had, what, 32 wins in Chicago altogether. I eclipsed that here the other night." The Clippers, who had six players score in double figures, trail Utah by one game in the race for the eighth and final Western Conference playoff berth. The Clippers are attempting to make the playoffs for the first time since 1997 and only the third time since moving from San Diego to Los Angeles in 1984. "I like the way we're playing," Clippers coach Alvin Gentry said. "We can't worry about the standings. The only way we're going to get to the playoffs is to win games. That's our goal, to make the playoffs." Richard Hamilton scored 21 points and Courtney Alexander added 13 for the Wizards, who have lost five straight, seven of nine since Michael Jordan underwent arthroscopic knee surgery, and 12 of 14 overall. They trail Charlotte by 1½ games for the last Eastern Conference playoff spot. "They were aggressive, they wanted it more than us," Hamilton said. "This is one of the few times we've been blown out all season. We've got to keep it together, hope we can get it turned around." The Clippers clinched the victory by scoring 10 straight points, including four each by Darius Miles and Olowokandi, for an 86-64 lead with 7:49 remaining. The Clippers outscored the Wizards 20-13 in the fourth quarter. "Defense is what gets you to the playoffs," Brand said. "The offensive skills, and the highlights -- that's just extra. That's all a bonus for us." Wizards coach Doug Collins made no excuses. Rather, he praised the Clippers. "I didn't know they were that good defensively, they're a very good defensive team," he said. "They got off to a great start, they got the ball inside. "The Clippers are fighting for position. Our guys just got a taste of what high-level basketball is. Looking at the Clippers' young players, we've got a long way to go." Hamilton scored six points as the Wizards went on a 13-7 run to start the second half to draw within nine points. But that's as close as they would get in the second half. Two free throws by Eric Piatkowski and a pair of baskets by Miles extended the Clippers' lead to 16 points late in the third period, and it was 76-62 entering the fourth. Brand had nine points, six rebounds, two assists and two blocks in the first quarter, which ended with the Clippers on top 28-18. It was only that close because the Wizards scored the last six points. The Clippers, who never trailed, led by as many as 17 points in the second quarter before settling for a 53-38 halftime lead.

Game notes
The game at Staples Center was played before a crowd of 20,282 -- the Clippers' seventh straight sellout and 16th of the season. ... The win was only the fourth for the Clippers in their last 15 games against the Wizards. ... The Clippers shoot for their first five-game winning streak since early in the 1995-96 season Friday night against the Los Angeles Lakers. The Clippers beat the Lakers 95-90 on Jan. 23 after losing twice to the two-time defending NBA champions earlier. ... The Clippers are three games over .500 this late in a season for the first time since March 15, 1992, when they were also 34-31. They finished 45-37 -- their last winning record. ... The Clippers outrebounded the Wizards 14-4 in the first quarter and 48-33 in the game.
